156
00:09:18,424 --> 00:09:20,785
First, why is alignment so important?

157
00:09:24,187 --> 00:09:28,048
So this is a cartoon by Henrik Nyberg, one of my favorite agilists.

158
00:09:29,769 --> 00:09:31,029
Why is alignment important?

159
00:09:34,991 --> 00:09:36,131
Would you say it's not funny?

160
00:09:37,012 --> 00:09:37,692
Yeah, I know.

161
00:09:37,712 --> 00:09:39,413
You just feel, oh gosh.

162
00:09:39,900 --> 00:09:43,062
So in this, like in any large scale human endeavor,

163
00:09:43,082 --> 00:09:45,964
you have teams working in parallel.

164
00:09:46,444 --> 00:09:47,605
Alignment is key.

165
00:09:49,026 --> 00:09:52,329
In this example, you have two teams working autonomously.

166
00:09:52,349 --> 00:09:55,411
And it's clear they understood the end goal, right?

167
00:09:55,451 --> 00:09:58,373
They needed to cross the expanse of water.

168
00:09:58,853 --> 00:09:59,854
So they had that end goal.

169
00:09:59,894 --> 00:10:01,495
Like they started out maybe in a huddle.

170
00:10:01,575 --> 00:10:03,917
Hey, guys, we're going to cross this expanse.

171
00:10:03,997 --> 00:10:05,138
Yeah, we know what to do.

172
00:10:06,722 --> 00:10:11,863
So they started out to achieve their goal, but they clearly lacked some sort of regular

173
00:10:11,923 --> 00:10:14,324
communication or coordination to stay aligned.

174
00:10:15,264 --> 00:10:17,285
Also dependency management.

175
00:10:17,625 --> 00:10:20,686
So the teams working in parallel had a huge dependency, right?

176
00:10:21,126 --> 00:10:23,207
They needed to connect or hook up.

177
00:10:24,407 --> 00:10:27,948
But that dependency was clearly not identified or managed.

178
00:10:31,049 --> 00:10:34,590
Famous example of a lack of alignment causing problems.

179
00:10:34,650 --> 00:10:35,770
Do you know what this is?

180
00:10:37,160 --> 00:10:41,201
It's the Mars Orbiter in 1999.

181
00:10:42,441 --> 00:10:46,463
So NASA lost $125 million Mars Orbiter.

182
00:10:47,483 --> 00:10:49,784
And the core problem was that Lockheed Martin,

183
00:10:50,304 --> 00:10:54,826
the engineering team that was building the software used,

184
00:10:56,826 --> 00:10:59,547
building the thruster software for the orbiter,

185
00:11:00,488 --> 00:11:02,968
used imperial English units of measurement.

186
00:11:03,802 --> 00:11:08,064
Well, the agency's team, building the software system,

187
00:11:08,104 --> 00:11:09,964
taking in the information, actually

188
00:11:10,044 --> 00:11:11,665
used the metric system of measurement.

189
00:11:12,545 --> 00:11:16,126
This caused the orbiter to lose navigation

190
00:11:16,186 --> 00:11:17,886
and actually crash into the planet.

191
00:11:19,227 --> 00:11:20,767
So they finally got there.

192
00:11:20,867 --> 00:11:22,028
It went all the way to Mars.

193
00:11:22,108 --> 00:11:22,728
It finally got there.

194
00:11:22,768 --> 00:11:23,688
They were going to celebrate.

195
00:11:24,128 --> 00:11:25,469
And then all of a sudden, it couldn't move,

196
00:11:25,529 --> 00:11:27,349
and it just went down and then crashed.

197
00:11:29,530 --> 00:11:32,291
They investigated and quickly found the misalignment.

198
00:11:33,114 --> 00:11:35,835
And that misalignment had existed for nearly 10 months,

199
00:11:36,435 --> 00:11:37,735
yet it had gone undetected.

200
00:11:38,455 --> 00:11:40,496
They didn't realize that they were using different systems

201
00:11:40,536 --> 00:11:40,976
of measurement.

202
00:11:41,356 --> 00:11:44,377
So the main point, teams of very smart people

203
00:11:44,457 --> 00:11:46,897
can get out of alignment and cause problems.

204
00:11:50,218 --> 00:11:52,798
So it's important to understand that when we have semi-autonomous

205
00:11:52,838 --> 00:11:54,939
team units working in parallel, there's

206
00:11:54,959 --> 00:11:59,600
a natural drift that occurs as time progresses.

207
00:11:59,700 --> 00:12:02,040
So I did this animation to.

208
00:12:02,652 --> 00:12:08,973
illustrate you have small divergences in understanding about scope or areas of responsibility that

209
00:12:08,993 --> 00:12:11,354
become wider as development goes on.

210
00:12:13,275 --> 00:12:19,156
If teams get more and more out of alignment, after a certain point, there's no one individual

211
00:12:19,196 --> 00:12:20,637
team has the power to correct it.

212
00:12:20,837 --> 00:12:24,058
They could maybe even see it coming and they just can't do anything.

213
00:12:25,938 --> 00:12:30,019
At Bungie, Patrick, the head of production for Destiny 2, would use the analogy of a

214
00:12:30,139 --> 00:12:31,300
fleet of sailboats.

