00:18:47,709 --> 00:18:49,651
that helps synchronize teams at that layer?

308
00:18:50,611 --> 00:18:51,412
Sure enough, there was.

309
00:18:52,651 --> 00:18:56,952
It was called Program Increment Planning, or PI planning.

310
00:18:58,192 --> 00:19:00,012
So bear with me, it's a little jargony,

311
00:19:00,172 --> 00:19:03,573
PI planning, Program Increment Planning.

312
00:19:03,633 --> 00:19:06,293
So what is a program increment?

313
00:19:06,933 --> 00:19:09,594
It's a collection of work that is the output of many teams.

314
00:19:10,434 --> 00:19:12,754
It has a time box iteration like a sprint,

315
00:19:13,635 --> 00:19:15,755
but the time box is in 12 weeks,

316
00:19:16,475 --> 00:19:18,555
or what would be six sprints.

317
00:19:19,136 --> 00:19:19,896
So it's typically.

318
00:19:23,390 --> 00:19:27,251
There was, so the PI planning ritual brings teams together in one place,

319
00:19:27,731 --> 00:19:30,952
one time to roughly plan a quarter's worth of work together

320
00:19:30,972 --> 00:19:34,332
and identify and resolve interdependencies.

321
00:19:35,653 --> 00:19:39,674
So the collection of quarterly scope in SAFE is called a release train.

322
00:19:41,634 --> 00:19:44,475
So we have the program increment planning happens at the beginning of

323
00:19:44,495 --> 00:19:47,736
the quarter. The quarterly release train, think about

324
00:19:47,776 --> 00:19:50,417
it as a container, like use the analogy of a train.

325
00:19:50,877 --> 00:19:52,837
It's a container like a train car.

326
00:19:53,711 --> 00:19:56,272
of work for that quarter.

327
00:19:56,292 --> 00:19:58,013
You put stuff onto the train car,

328
00:19:58,613 --> 00:20:02,796
and it's planned in that big room PI planning exercise.

329
00:20:03,096 --> 00:20:04,977
And then like a train, it leaves the station

330
00:20:04,997 --> 00:20:06,637
to get developed over six sprints

331
00:20:06,698 --> 00:20:09,739
until it pulls into the next station 12 weeks later.

332
00:20:09,759 --> 00:20:12,981
So PI planning then is a process of determining

333
00:20:13,001 --> 00:20:15,102
what do you want to put on the next train that's leaving?

334
00:20:16,102 --> 00:20:18,023
You can think, what is the most important feature

335
00:20:18,363 --> 00:20:19,704
that we need to learn from this quarter?

336
00:20:20,330 --> 00:20:24,493
You know, are there features that contain a high amount of uncertainty that we need to reduce?

337
00:20:25,193 --> 00:20:26,914
What are some of the big bets we want to prove out?

338
00:20:27,334 --> 00:20:31,757
Let's put it on the train, get it done, pull it in the station, and then we'll reassess.

339
00:20:33,338 --> 00:20:37,540
So PI planning, I had a name for it, but how does one do PI planning?

340
00:20:40,141 --> 00:20:41,062
I wanted to know more.

341
00:20:42,883 --> 00:20:45,424
So I stumbled onto a case study by Henrik Nyberg,

342
00:20:45,484 --> 00:20:48,186
who's an influential agilist and agile thought leader.

343
00:20:48,765 --> 00:20:53,528
who has a really playful, accessible approach to scaled agile,

344
00:20:53,568 --> 00:20:55,409
which you need because it can be pretty daunting.

345
00:20:56,890 --> 00:20:59,672
He's worked with both Spotify and Lego,

346
00:20:59,712 --> 00:21:02,234
and you can go online, I see YouTube videos.

347
00:21:02,274 --> 00:21:07,197
He'll walk you through some of the scaled agile rituals

348
00:21:07,217 --> 00:21:09,058
that he has experimented with.

349
00:21:10,039 --> 00:21:12,100
So I took the case study for Lego.

350
00:21:14,204 --> 00:21:18,747
I was like, literally I took the case study, I got the YouTube video and I transcribed

351
00:21:18,847 --> 00:21:23,870
it and put it into a document and worked with Bungee production.

352
00:21:24,390 --> 00:21:26,791
We looked through it and we figured out how could this work for us?

353
00:21:27,272 --> 00:21:30,313
How could we do PI planning or big room planning?

354
00:21:32,875 --> 00:21:37,477
So we used it as a template for starting PI planning at Bungee.

355
00:21:41,840 --> 00:21:42,540
This concept of...

356
00:21:42,993 --> 00:21:46,075
quarterly big room planning exercise, an epic sink.

357
00:21:48,016 --> 00:21:48,937
What could this get us?

358
00:21:48,997 --> 00:21:51,738
We had to weigh the cost-benefit.

359
00:21:53,219 --> 00:21:56,581
So instead of drift over quarter,

360
00:21:57,541 --> 00:22:00,003
we would tightly sink every 12 weeks.

361
00:22:01,083 --> 00:22:05,846
And then we would develop and then sink, develop, sink.

362
00:22:08,350 --> 00:22:12,773
A wonderful byproduct is that we could actually allow a measure of freedom and autonomy for

363
00:22:12,813 --> 00:22:17,836
the teams during the development cycle, during the sprints, knowing that we'd be regularly

364
00:22:17,896 --> 00:22:21,638
coming together into alignment in 12 weeks to tighten things up.

365
00:22:22,078 --> 00:22:25,701
So it reduced the amount of micromanagement every sprint.

366
00:22:25,761 --> 00:22:27,382
It's like, no, give them freedom.

367
00:22:27,422 --> 00:22:30,183
They're getting their up, and then we get on course.

368
00:22:30,223 --> 00:22:34,206
Like the analogy of a flotilla of sailboats.

369
00:22:34,486 --> 00:22:37,608
You know, one goes off, you rein it back in.

370
00:22:40,534 --> 00:22:45,896
Our pitch, so the concept of PI planning in hand

371
00:22:45,976 --> 00:22:47,396
and understanding the mechanics,

372
00:22:48,016 --> 00:22:49,717
Bungee Production made the pitch

373
00:22:50,277 --> 00:22:53,278
to the Destiny 2 development teams and leadership.

374
00:22:55,238 --> 00:22:58,319
The pitch was, what if we got everybody in a room

375
00:22:58,799 --> 00:23:01,220
at the same time, face-to-face,

376
00:23:03,020 --> 00:23:04,721
to sync on the vision for the quarter,

377
00:23:05,201 --> 00:23:08,162
plan the team's work, identify and discuss

378
00:23:08,182 --> 00:23:09,362
and resolve dependencies?

379
00:23:12,418 --> 00:23:14,779
Bunjee's first planning day was born.

380
00:23:15,820 --> 00:23:18,761
So our Epic Sync, our PI planning, we call,

381
00:23:19,821 --> 00:23:21,822
it took us a long time to come up with the term,

382
00:23:22,382 --> 00:23:23,242
planning day.

383
00:23:26,483 --> 00:23:29,244
If you try it, you can come up with something different,

384
00:23:29,865 --> 00:23:32,085
but we call it planning day and it stuck.

385
00:23:35,747 --> 00:23:38,288
So as you can imagine, there was initial skepticism.

386
00:23:39,088 --> 00:23:41,549
Take the entire development team of Destiny 2.

387
00:23:42,795 --> 00:23:50,517
offline for a day. Are you kidding? It was a new idea and fairly large undertaking. It

388
00:23:50,537 --> 00:23:56,818
was a bold move. So you might be wondering, you know, how did you convince people? Well,

389
00:23:56,838 --> 00:24:01,559
there was a general recognition that the way we planned and communicated, largely through

390
00:24:01,619 --> 00:24:06,039
indirect means, was not optimal for the highly integrated development work we were doing

391
00:24:06,099 --> 00:24:12,020
on Destiny 2. So we had an idea to try that had been proven successful in other companies.

392
00:24:12,951 --> 00:24:16,072
Most all were willing to try it at least once to see how it goes.

393
00:24:17,852 --> 00:24:19,433
So that's how the production worked.

394
00:24:19,493 --> 00:24:21,793
It's like, OK, let's just try it once.

395
00:24:21,853 --> 00:24:23,674
If we hate it, we'll never do it again.

396
00:24:25,334 --> 00:24:27,975
The spirit of being willing to try something bold like this

397
00:24:28,095 --> 00:24:31,436
and learn from it is one of the many things I love about working at Bungie.

398
00:24:34,716 --> 00:24:38,817
So we went from this to this.

