Having everyone sit in one room and really work through their problems so that you can come out of a day with a really clear understanding of what your team is doing and what all your team needs to focus on.

740
00:45:39,319 --> 00:45:41,001
Yeah, yeah, yeah. We're going to do Tantrums.

741
00:45:49,981 --> 00:45:59,086
It requires them to go and talk to their teammates and figure out what they need to do and really

742
00:45:59,106 --> 00:46:00,506
make sure that the problem is fully solved.

743
00:46:01,807 --> 00:46:05,549
And then we've instituted things like making sure they're resolved so there's that follow-up.

744
00:46:06,184 --> 00:46:10,645
And so it's exposed it to the leadership, to their team, to every other team.

745
00:46:10,665 --> 00:46:12,146
It really does increase that accountability.

746
00:46:12,166 --> 00:46:14,947
You're really challenging yourself to ask the question of,

747
00:46:15,107 --> 00:46:17,548
is the students doing this? Does everyone know about it?

748
00:46:22,970 --> 00:46:24,971
You come out of this understanding your priorities

749
00:46:25,191 --> 00:46:27,152
and really challenging yourself to see what you can build.

750
00:46:27,692 --> 00:46:31,033
Those people can then go out of this day with a really clear mandate

751
00:46:31,093 --> 00:46:32,414
about what they're doing the next day.

752
00:46:33,045 --> 00:46:37,347
The rancor that you add by really forcing yourself to drill down and ask tough questions

753
00:46:37,367 --> 00:46:40,949
can allow for the project to be better scoped and ultimately more successful.

754
00:47:06,334 --> 00:47:08,475
Yay, dependencies resolved.

755
00:47:10,517 --> 00:47:11,218
Celebrate.

756
00:47:11,318 --> 00:47:12,099
You celebrate.

757
00:47:13,820 --> 00:47:16,442
All right, so I just want to wrap up

758
00:47:16,482 --> 00:47:19,985
with a few additional slides and then some lessons learned.

759
00:47:20,646 --> 00:47:23,508
And then I'd be happy to answer questions in the overflow area

760
00:47:23,869 --> 00:47:24,309
afterwards.

761
00:47:25,470 --> 00:47:27,312
So you may be wondering, how do we keep tabs

762
00:47:27,372 --> 00:47:29,634
on these dependencies after planning day?

763
00:47:29,654 --> 00:47:30,715
Because everyone gets excited.

764
00:47:30,735 --> 00:47:32,296
You can see they're collaborating and having fun.

765
00:47:32,336 --> 00:47:34,278
And then it's like, OK, where did the dependency go?

766
00:47:35,004 --> 00:47:40,287
Well, it's in their backlog, but it's tracked separately

767
00:47:40,367 --> 00:47:43,069
with a midpoint check-in we call dependency check-in.

768
00:47:43,469 --> 00:47:45,190
So this is done on-site at Bungie.

769
00:47:45,230 --> 00:47:46,611
We have a conference room you'll see here.

770
00:47:47,051 --> 00:47:49,592
We have teams set up in different parts of the room.

771
00:47:50,133 --> 00:47:55,195
And you come there, you prepare basically the product

772
00:47:55,236 --> 00:47:57,837
owners and the producers only, so we don't have the full

773
00:47:57,877 --> 00:47:58,557
teams there.

774
00:47:59,138 --> 00:48:01,359
We prepare to check in on dependent work.

775
00:48:01,539 --> 00:48:03,640
Go around the room, have conversations you need.

776
00:48:04,451 --> 00:48:09,796
And your team is done when those depending on you

777
00:48:09,856 --> 00:48:11,258
have gotten what they need from the sink.

778
00:48:11,638 --> 00:48:13,159
So we actually do this ritual where

779
00:48:13,240 --> 00:48:14,160
you're about to leave the room.

780
00:48:14,200 --> 00:48:16,523
It's like, OK, I'm on the combatants team.

781
00:48:16,583 --> 00:48:17,764
Anybody need to talk to me?

782
00:48:18,505 --> 00:48:19,466
No, OK, I'm leaving.

783
00:48:19,606 --> 00:48:20,567
Or yes, I do.

784
00:48:21,107 --> 00:48:24,230
So it's really an agreement between the people in the room

785
00:48:24,270 --> 00:48:26,753
that they get what they need out of dependency check-in.

786
00:48:28,294 --> 00:48:28,795
So we've

787
00:48:29,988 --> 00:48:36,052
done this almost 12 or 13 times now with many different releases and we've

788
00:48:36,092 --> 00:48:41,015
tweaked it. We've never done it the same way twice but it always has the same

789
00:48:41,095 --> 00:48:45,918
elements as I said those basic elements of planning and dependency resolution

790
00:48:47,279 --> 00:48:51,262
but we played with some things I wanted to share you share with you what we

791
00:48:51,282 --> 00:48:54,964
learned. So one of the things is how much prep do you do? How much prep do the

792
00:48:55,004 --> 00:48:58,747
teams do? Because you have that that part of the agenda where the teams get to

793
00:48:59,278 --> 00:49:02,781
actually work together and plan out.

794
00:49:02,821 --> 00:49:06,985
So the first time we didn't do that much prep,

795
00:49:07,786 --> 00:49:10,168
and then we overcompensated the next time,

796
00:49:10,248 --> 00:49:12,670
and the product owners did all the planning

797
00:49:12,690 --> 00:49:14,352
and the teams felt left out,

798
00:49:14,452 --> 00:49:16,754
so we then just had to loosen it.

799
00:49:16,814 --> 00:49:18,275
So it's like Goldilocks.

800
00:49:19,136 --> 00:49:21,198
It's too hot, too cold, just right.

801
00:49:22,953 --> 00:49:26,135
Wrap up, how to share out the team's plans efficiently.

802
00:49:26,555 --> 00:49:27,855
So you have all the teams, the plan,

803
00:49:27,895 --> 00:49:29,456
how do you get that visibility?

804
00:49:29,576 --> 00:49:32,397
It is in TFS, but that's not really effective.

805
00:49:32,877 --> 00:49:33,898
So at first, as I said,

806
00:49:33,918 --> 00:49:36,399
we tried that team science fair format,

807
00:49:36,559 --> 00:49:41,261
but it just was unuseful.

808
00:49:41,441 --> 00:49:43,441
But what we did is we brought those team boards back

809
00:49:43,521 --> 00:49:45,982
and we would display them back at Bungie

810
00:49:46,062 --> 00:49:48,263
so that anybody that wanted to actually look deeper

811
00:49:48,984 --> 00:49:51,785
into the team's scope for that quarter could.

812
00:49:54,574 --> 00:49:56,636
Do all team members have to stay for the entire day?

813
00:49:57,657 --> 00:50:01,642
Getting an artist to stay in a room planning for a whole day

814
00:50:01,662 --> 00:50:03,223
is not the easiest thing.

815
00:50:04,404 --> 00:50:07,247
So while people really saw the value,

816
00:50:09,390 --> 00:50:12,533
it was important when we first did it, we had mandatory.

817
00:50:12,653 --> 00:50:13,874
All the teams have to show up.

818
00:50:14,608 --> 00:50:17,649
We gave them snacks and food, so, you know, made it worth their while.

819
00:50:18,109 --> 00:50:20,610
But once we did it, people saw the value.

820
00:50:20,950 --> 00:50:25,031
So it was not as much of a hard sell after that.

821
00:50:25,511 --> 00:50:28,352
But what we've done is we allow the teams to self-organize.

822
00:50:28,912 --> 00:50:33,674
They can determine who needs to be there for the dependencies check-in section.

823
00:50:35,775 --> 00:50:40,056
So I really recommend if you do this, gather data after every planning day.

824
00:50:40,756 --> 00:50:43,617
This is something that you'll want to continually refine and reflect.

825
00:50:44,015 --> 00:50:47,696
So I use SurveyMonkey, send out SurveyMonkeys.

826
00:50:48,036 --> 00:50:50,957
Here's an example of one recently.

827
00:50:51,697 --> 00:50:53,298
Crossing planning day, was it valuable

828
00:50:53,318 --> 00:50:56,219
in gaining crossing visibility and identifying dependencies?

829
00:50:56,599 --> 00:51:00,400
So we have roughly like 89% said yes.

830
00:51:02,521 --> 00:51:04,801
Also, does your team have a winter build plan

831
00:51:04,841 --> 00:51:05,602
that they believe in?

832
00:51:05,622 --> 00:51:07,982
Because that's what we want to come out with.

833
00:51:08,002 --> 00:51:09,103
Do you have a plan that you believe in?

834
00:51:09,243 --> 00:51:09,763
I can't believe it.

835
00:51:10,563 --> 00:51:11,203
I can't believe it.

836
00:51:11,243 --> 00:51:11,604
90% said yes.

837
00:51:13,477 --> 00:51:18,661
So that confidence that they're exuding, we have confidence in our plans.

838
00:51:20,863 --> 00:51:23,745
Briefly, many configurations of planning day.

839
00:51:23,805 --> 00:51:29,929
We've done large off-site, mid-off-site, mixed off-site, on-site, and all on-site.

840
00:51:29,990 --> 00:51:34,973
So you can do this, you know, if you have a big room at your studio.

841
00:51:35,734 --> 00:51:40,157
There is a value in taking people off-site, so I'd really recommend trying that first

842
00:51:40,317 --> 00:51:42,839
because then people are away from their...

843
00:51:43,553 --> 00:51:44,313
workstations.

844
00:51:47,735 --> 00:51:50,677
OK, so I wanted to just recap here, and then I'll give you

845
00:51:50,697 --> 00:51:52,478
some takeaways, and then we'll be done.

846
00:51:53,379 --> 00:51:56,161
Planning day ritual, what did we gain?

847
00:51:56,481 --> 00:51:58,582
So we saw a positive effect.

848
00:51:59,063 --> 00:52:01,544
Our first major winter build, after the first two planning

849
00:52:01,584 --> 00:52:05,747
days, had more complete work in it than we had previously.

850
00:52:06,968 --> 00:52:10,210
So we had regular alignment with all the teams, with the

851
00:52:10,230 --> 00:52:11,270
product vision and pillars.

852
00:52:12,656 --> 00:52:17,419
What we got from planning day, we had dependent work identified and tracked for the first time.

853
00:52:18,959 --> 00:52:22,581
We had authentic cross-team commitments made face-to-face, so we did

854
00:52:22,621 --> 00:52:26,764
that human proximity engineering to get those commitments face-to-face.

855
00:52:27,084 --> 00:52:31,306
And there's nothing like someone, there's nothing like the combatants team telling,

856
00:52:31,586 --> 00:52:35,128
or the, you know, the visual effects team telling the combatants team,

857
00:52:35,168 --> 00:52:36,449
you're going to get that effect.

858
00:52:36,869 --> 00:52:41,092
Like face-to-face, there's something that increases the accountability.

859
00:52:42,193 --> 00:52:44,655
And it's efficient and transparent decision-making

860
00:52:45,535 --> 00:52:48,136
with the decisions reported out to everybody.

861
00:52:49,257 --> 00:52:51,478
All told, it increases the predictability.

862
00:52:51,738 --> 00:52:53,319
Now we know better what we're getting

863
00:52:53,339 --> 00:52:55,360
at the end of the quarter in our quarterly build

864
00:52:55,880 --> 00:52:58,641
and our agility, our ability to pivot if need be.

